{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17591867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17591867"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:07:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:07:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15213"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15213"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.48,0.14,0.17,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7904"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7904"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98389"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8572"},{"type":"tags","id":"8741"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21321"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are several different types of carcinoma of the oesophagus. Adenocarcinoma of the oesophagus is a particularly aggressive malignancy with an increasing incidence in Western countries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct regarding oesophageal adenocarcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Characteristically is found in the upper oesophagus","More common in men than women","Most common in South East Asia","Most common in women","Radiotherapy alone is first-line treatment"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOesophageal adenocarcinoma has distinct epidemiological and clinical features that distinguish it from other oesophageal malignancies. \u003Cstrong\u003EMore common in men than women\u003C/strong\u003E is correct, as this malignancy predominantly affects men with a male:female ratio of approximately 7:1. The main risk factors include chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, Barrett\u0027s oesophagus, obesity, and smoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMost common in women\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emost common in South East Asia\u003C/strong\u003E are both incorrect as oesophageal adenocarcinoma shows a strong male predominance and is more prevalent in Western countries rather than South East Asia. \u003Cstrong\u003ECharacteristically is found in the upper oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E does not accurately describe this malignancy as it usually develops in the lower third of the oesophagus. \u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy alone is first-line treatment\u003C/strong\u003E does not reflect current management approaches, as multimodal therapy including surgery is typically required for optimal outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Oesophageal adenocarcinoma predominantly affects men with a male:female ratio of approximately 7:1","Oesophageal adenocarcinoma is relatively radioresistant compared to squamous cell carcinoma","Barrett\u0027s oesophagus is the main precursor lesion for oesophageal adenocarcinoma"],"references":["DiSiena M, Perelman A. Birk J, et al. Esophageal Cancer: An Updated Review. South Med J 2021; 114:161-67"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98389"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","